<promed@promedmail.org>
[The significance of this report is uncertain, unless there are unstated
pathological features. HTLV-I was isolated first from a cell line derived
from splenic cells taken from a patient suffering from a hairy cell
leukemia, now considered to be a fortuitous association. HTLV-II is known
now to be endemic among several Amerindian populations in North, Central
and South America. In industrialized countries HTLV-II is prevalent among
drug abusers and is spread by contaminated needles and by heterosexual
transmission. In the developing world breastfeeding may be the predominant
route of transmission. Biologically, the HTLVs differ from HIV in their
greater genetic stability and their characteristic patterns of geographic
distribution. The present distribution of HTLV-II in the world has been
interpreted to be a consequence of the introduction of HTLV-II into the New
world at the time of the initial settlement of the American continent by
the ancestors of the present day native Americans some 20 000 to 40 000
years ago, followed by more recent dissemination from one or a few sources.
This interpretation is confounded, however, by the absence of any remnant
of an endemic population in Asia and presence of HTLV-II in remote Pygmy
communities in Africa. - Mod.CP
